## 8. Code Quality & Maintainability

### 8.1 Large files violate single-responsibility
- `data-processors.js` (1515 lines) handles line data slicing, spectrogram chunk extraction, threshold calculation, offset application, and display metadata creation. This should be split into `data-processors/lineData.js`, `data-processors/spectrogramData.js`, and `data-processors/thresholds.js`.
- `components.py` (3169 lines) contains every Bokeh widget class. Splitting into `components/timeseries.py`, `components/spectrogram.py`, `components/panels.py` would reduce merge conflicts.

### 8.2 Magic numbers scattered across JS and Python
- `MIN_COVERAGE_RATIO = 0.98` in JS, `LOG_VIEW_BUFFER_FRACTION_DEFAULT` in Python, `HEAVY_UPDATE_THROTTLE_MS = 50` in `app.js`. These should be centralized in `config.py`/`CHART_SETTINGS` and mirrored to JS via a JSON payload at init.

### 8.3 Inconsistent null/undefined guarding
- Some functions use `if (!data)` (catches `null`, `undefined`, `false`, `0`, `''`), others use `if (data == null)` (catches only `null`/`undefined`), and others use `if (typeof data === 'undefined')`. This inconsistency makes refactoring risky.

### 8.4 Python `sys.path.insert` hacks in multiple files
- `data_processors.py`, `dashBuilder.py`, and others manually manipulate `sys.path` to resolve imports. This is a smell that the package structure or launch configuration is incorrect. It should not be necessary in a properly installed package.

